      { id: 'B', text: 'B. Increase the number of epochs' },
      { id: 'C', text: 'C. Decrease the learning rate' },
      { id: 'D', text: 'D. Increase the batch size Explanation: Overall explanation Incorrect Answers: A. Increase the learning rate While adjusting the learning rate can impact the speed of convergence, it does not directly address the issue of underutilized TPUs. Inappropriate increases in the learning rate can also lead to training instability or divergence. B. Increase the number of epochs Increasing the number of epochs means that the model will go through the dataset more times, which could potentially lead to overfitting and does not directly contribute to better TPU utilization. C. Decrease the learning rate Decreasing the learning rate can make the training process more stable, but it typically slows down convergence and does not address the issue of TPU underutilization. Correct Answer D. Increase the batch size TPUs are designed to process large amounts of data in parallel. A larger batch size means that more data is processed simultaneously, allowing the TPU to work more efficiently and closer to its full capacity. This can significantly reduce the time per epoch by making better use of the TPU\'s parallel processing capabilities. By increasing the batch size, you reduce the number of steps required per epoch because more examples are processed in each step. This can lead to faster training times as long as the TPU memory can accommodate the larger batches without leading to out-of-memory errors. While extremely large batch sizes may sometimes negatively affect model generalization, finding the right balance can provide both efficient hardware utilization and good model performance. It\'s important to monitor the model\'s training and validation metrics to ensure that the increased batch size does not harm the model\'s ability to learn effectively. Reference: https://cloud.google.com/tpu/docs/performance-guide' }
